Add mock address book contacts and an interaction to show the contact autocomplete dropdown in the Send view.

**Why this is impactful**: The Send view is a critical user flow. The contact autocomplete dropdown (app/views/Send/index.tsx lines 229-250) is a floating overlay that could easily break with CSS changes. Testing it catches z-index, positioning, and rendering bugs.

**What to add to mockState** in scripts/_screenshot_main.cjs:
Add an `addressBook` field to `mockState.main`:
```js
addressBook: {
  'contact-1': { name: 'Alice', address: '0xaaaa111122223333444455556666777788889999', notes: '' },
  'contact-2': { name: 'Bob Vance', address: '0xbbbb111122223333444455556666777788889999', notes: 'Cold storage' },
  'contact-3': { name: 'Treasury', address: '0xcccc111122223333444455556666777788889999', notes: 'DAO multisig' }
}
```

**Interaction to add** to the `interactions` object in _screenshot_main.cjs:
```js
send: [
  {
    name: 'send-contact-autocomplete',
    js: \`(() => {
      // Type a letter into the recipient input to trigger contact autocomplete
      const input = document.querySelector('input[placeholder*="0x"]');
      if (!input) return 'no recipient input found';
      // Set value and dispatch input event to trigger React state update
      const nativeInputValueSetter = Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(window.HTMLInputElement.prototype, 'value').set;
      nativeInputValueSetter.call(input, 'a');
      input.dispatchEvent(new Event('input', { bubbles: true }));
      input.dispatchEvent(new Event('change', { bubbles: true }));
      input.focus();
      return 'typed in recipient, focused input';
    })()\`
  }
]
```

**Store path**: `useAddressBook` in app/store.ts reads from `state.main.addressBook`.

**Files to modify**: scripts/_screenshot_main.cjs (add addressBook to mockState.main, add send interaction)
**Source reference**: app/views/Send/index.tsx lines 50-58 for suggestion filtering, lines 229-250 for dropdown rendering
**Validate**: Run 'npm run test:screenshots' and verify the new screenshot shows the autocomplete dropdown with 'Alice' visible below the recipient input.

Add a screenshot interaction test for the Settings view that clicks 'Reset All Settings' to reveal the danger zone confirmation modal.

**Why this is impactful**: The Settings view has a destructive action (reset all settings) behind a confirmation modal. Testing this catches modal rendering, backdrop, button styling, and the red danger-zone styling. It's the only modal in Settings and tests the Modal component in a different context than add-contact/add-token.

**Pattern to follow**: See the existing 'contacts' interaction in scripts/_screenshot_main.cjs lines 222-233.

**What to add** to the `interactions` object:
```js
settings: [
  {
    name: 'settings-reset-modal',
    js: \`(() => {
      // Scroll to bottom first to find the Reset button, then click it
      const main = document.querySelector('main');
      if (main) main.scrollTop = main.scrollHeight;
      // Find the 'Reset All Settings' button in the danger zone section
      const buttons = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('button'));
      const resetBtn = buttons.find(b => b.textContent.includes('Reset All Settings'));
      if (resetBtn) { resetBtn.click(); return 'clicked: ' + resetBtn.textContent.trim(); }
      return 'no Reset All Settings button found, buttons: ' + buttons.map(b => b.textContent.trim().substring(0, 30)).join(', ');
    })()\`
  }
]
```

**Files to modify**: scripts/_screenshot_main.cjs (add to interactions object)
**Source reference**: app/views/Settings/index.tsx lines 139-156 for the reset button and Modal
**Validate**: Run 'npm run test:screenshots' and verify the new screenshot shows a modal with 'Reset All Settings' title, warning text, and Cancel/Reset buttons.

Add a screenshot interaction test for the Portfolio view that clicks a section header to collapse/expand it, testing the collapsible section UI.

**Why this is impactful**: The Portfolio view organizes balances into collapsible 'By Chain' and 'By Account' sections. Testing the collapsed state catches CSS transition bugs, content hiding, and chevron icon rotation. It also validates that multi-account/multi-chain balance aggregation renders correctly.

**Pattern to follow**: See the existing interactions in scripts/_screenshot_main.cjs.

**What to add** to the `interactions` object:
```js
portfolio: [
  {
    name: 'portfolio-collapsed',
    js: \`(() => {
      // Find and click the first collapsible section header (should be 'By Chain' or similar)
      // Look for buttons with chevron/arrow icons or section headers that toggle
      const buttons = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('main button'));
      const sectionBtn = buttons.find(b => b.textContent.includes('By Chain') || b.textContent.includes('Chain') || b.querySelector('svg'));
      if (sectionBtn) { sectionBtn.click(); return 'clicked section: ' + sectionBtn.textContent.trim().substring(0, 50); }
      // Fallback: click any heading-like button
      const headings = buttons.filter(b => b.className.includes('font-medium') || b.className.includes('uppercase'));
      if (headings[0]) { headings[0].click(); return 'clicked heading: ' + headings[0].textContent.trim().substring(0, 50); }
      return 'no collapsible section found, buttons: ' + buttons.length;
    })()\`
  }
]
```

**Files to modify**: scripts/_screenshot_main.cjs (add to interactions object)
**Source reference**: app/views/Portfolio/index.tsx lines 146-161 for the collapsible sections
**Validate**: Run 'npm run test:screenshots' and verify the new screenshot shows a collapsed section (content hidden, chevron rotated or section header visible without children).

